data.enText: only to be used by one particular person or group; only given to one particular person or group
data.chText: （个人或集体）专用的，专有的，独有的，独占的

data.enText: The hotel has exclusive access to the beach.
data.chText: 这家旅馆有通向海滩的专用通道。

data.enText: exclusive rights to televise the World Cup
data.chText: 世界杯赛的独家电视播放权

data.enText: His mother has told ‘The Times’ about his death in an exclusive interview (= not given to any other newspaper) .
data.chText: 他的母亲在接受《泰晤士报》的独家采访时谈到他的死亡。

data.enText: not very willing to allow new people to become members, especially if they are from a lower social class
data.chText: 排外的；不愿接收新成员（尤指较低社会阶层）的

data.enText: He belongs to an exclusive club.
data.chText: 他参加的是一个上层人士俱乐部。

data.enText: of a high quality and expensive and therefore not often bought or used by most people
not able to exist or be a true statement at the same time as sth else
The two options are not mutually exclusive (= you can have them both) .
data.chText: 这两种选择并不相互排斥。

data.enText: The price is for accommodation only, exclusive of meals.
data.chText: 此价只包括住宿，饭费除外。

data.enText: a charity that relies almost exclusively on voluntary contributions
data.chText: 几乎全靠志愿力量的慈善机构

data.enText: an item of news or a story about famous people that is published in only one newspaper or magazine
data.chText: 独家新闻；独家专文；独家报道

word_means: 专用的，专有的，独有的，独占的
simple_means.memory_skill: ex- 出,出去 + clus 关闭 + -ive 形容词后缀

means: (个人或集体)专用的，专有的，独有的，独占的
不愿接收新成员(尤指较低社会阶层)的

tr: a news report that is reported first by one news organization
example: he got a scoop on the bribery of city officials

tr: not divided among or brought to bear on more than one object or objective
example: judging a contest with a single eye

tr: especially all but a particular group or minority
not divided or shared with others
example: they have exclusive use of the machine

example.ex: He is already a member of Britain's most exclusive club...
example.tran: 他已经是英国最高级俱乐部的成员了。

example.ex: The City was criticised for being too exclusive and uncompetitive.
example.tran: 伦敦城被指责过于奢华和缺乏竞争力。

value.def: If you describe something as exclusive, you mean that it is limited to people who have a lot of money or who belong to a high social class, and is therefore not available to everyone.

example.ex: ...a rising middle class, which objected to the exclusiveness of the traditional elite.
example.tran: 反对传统精英奢华生活的新兴中产阶级

example.ex: ...a company with a reputation for exclusivity.
Our group will have exclusive use of a 60-foot boat...
example.tran: 我们小组将独用一条60英尺长的船。

example.ex: Many of their cheeses are exclusive to our stores in Britain.
example.tran: 在英国，他们生产的奶酪很多只在我们商店出售。

value.def: Something that is exclusive is used or owned by only one person or group, and not shared with anyone else.

example.ex: Only 250 are to be sold in Europe, so exclusivity is guaranteed.
example.tran: 在欧洲仅售250辆，所以可以保证与众不同。

example.ex: He told the magazine in an exclusive interview: 'All my problems stem from drink'.
example.tran: 他在接受一家杂志社的独家采访时说：“我所有的问题都是饮酒造成的。”

posc.def: An exclusive is an exclusive article or report.

example.ex: Some papers thought they had an exclusive.
example.tran: 一些报纸认为自己是独家报道。

value.def: If a newspaper, magazine, or broadcasting organization describes one of its reports as exclusive, they mean that it is a special report which does not appear in any other publication or on any other channel.

example.ex: All charges for service are exclusive of value added tax...
example.tran: 所有服务费都不包括增值税。

example.ex: Skiing weekends cost £58 (exclusive of travel and accommodation).
example.tran: 周末滑雪价格为58英镑（不含交通和住宿费）。

value.def: If a company states that its prices, goods, or services are exclusive of something, that thing is not included in the stated price, although it usually still has to be paid for.

example.ex: They both have learnt that ambition and successful fatherhood can be mutually exclusive.
example.tran: 他们两个人都认识到了追求理想和做个好父亲不能两者兼顾。

value.def: If two things are mutually exclusive, they are separate and very different from each other, so that it is impossible for them to exist or happen together.
value.tran: 相互排斥的;互不相容的
